// Borromean Rings -- three linked rings where no two are linked
//
// Remove any one ring and the other two fall apart.
// In code: three modules where no two share state directly,
// but all three share a dependency that links them.
//
// Module A depends on Config
// Module B depends on Config
// Module C depends on Config
// A-B: not linked (don't share state)
// B-C: not linked (don't share state)
// A-C: not linked (don't share state)
// A-B-C: linked through Config (remove Config and all three are independent)
//
// This is the microservices coupling antipattern: services that appear
// independent but are secretly linked through a shared database/config/cache.
//
// The Borromean property: you can't detect the coupling by looking at
// any pair of modules. You have to look at all three together.
// Pairwise independent, collectively entangled.
//
// Unlinking: extract Config into explicit message contracts per pair.
// The Borromean rings become three unknots.

(config: Process { op: 'shared_config', label: 'the hidden link' })

// Ring A: auth service
(a_init: Process { op: 'read_config', module: 'auth' })
(a_work: Process { op: 'authenticate' })
(a_emit: Process { op: 'emit_token' })

// Ring B: data service
(b_init: Process { op: 'read_config', module: 'data' })
(b_work: Process { op: 'query_store' })
(b_emit: Process { op: 'emit_result' })

// Ring C: notification service
(c_init: Process { op: 'read_config', module: 'notify' })
(c_work: Process { op: 'send_notification' })
(c_emit: Process { op: 'emit_status' })

// Each ring reads from shared config (the hidden link)
(config)-[:FORK]->(a_init, b_init, c_init)

// Ring A cycle
(a_init)-[:PROCESS]->(a_work)
(a_work)-[:PROCESS]->(a_emit)

// Ring B cycle
(b_init)-[:PROCESS]->(b_work)
(b_work)-[:PROCESS]->(b_emit)

// Ring C cycle
(c_init)-[:PROCESS]->(c_work)
(c_work)-[:PROCESS]->(c_emit)

// The Borromean link: all three fold back through config
(a_emit)-[:PROCESS { strategy: 'merge-all' }]->(config)
(b_emit)-[:PROCESS { strategy: 'merge-all' }]->(config)
(c_emit)-[:PROCESS { strategy: 'merge-all' }]->(config)

// Borromean property: remove any one ring's connection to config
// and the other two are independent (no shared edges).
// But with all three connected, they are collectively entangled.
//
// Untangled form:
// Replace shared config with explicit per-pair contracts:
//   (a_emit)-[:PROCESS { op: 'message' }]->(b_init)
//   (b_emit)-[:PROCESS { op: 'message' }]->(c_init)
// The FORK through config dissolves. Three unknots.
//
// This is the microservices lesson: if your services share a database,
// they're Borromean rings. Make the dependencies explicit and the
// rings unlink. The coupling was always there -- the Borromean
// topology just made it invisible to pairwise inspection.
